---
const loops = [
  {
    step: "01",
    title: "Frame the work before the agent starts",
    body:
      "Turn a loose request into context, scope, acceptance criteria, and constraints the agent can actually follow."
  },
  {
    step: "02",
    title: "Run the implementation inside a known system",
    body:
      "Give the agent the repo map, the active contracts, the relevant docs, and the operational commands before it edits."
  },
  {
    step: "03",
    title: "Verify against the promise, not just the build",
    body:
      "Check behavior, docs, public claims, edge cases, and workflow impact before treating a change as done."
  },
  {
    step: "04",
    title: "Ship with the server state still visible",
    body:
      "Keep environments, processes, tunnels, publishing, health, and logs close enough to the agent workflow to act on them."
  }
];
---

<section class="section">
  <div class="section-heading">
    <p class="eyebrow">The Agent Loop</p>
    <h2>ShipFlow covers the work around the agent, not only the prompt you send it.</h2>
    <p>
      The useful question is not whether AI can write code. It can. The useful
      question is whether your system can direct, inspect, run, and explain that
      work after the first answer arrives.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="card-grid">
    {
      loops.map((loop) => (
        <article class="card loop-card">
          <span>{loop.step}</span>
          <h3>{loop.title}</h3>
          <p>{loop.body}</p>
        </article>
      ))
    }
  </div>
</section>
